<p></p>.<p>
Red streaks on the skin are a characteristic sign of an infection of the skin or subcutaneous tissues, especially when the infection is spreading from its original site. In this case, other symptoms, such as <a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/pain_management/article.htm" rel="dt" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">pain</a>, tenderness, swelling, and warmth typically accompany the red streaks. Red streaks can also be a sign of injury, such as a scratch injury. Striae, sometimes referred to as <a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/stretch_marks/article.htm" rel="dt" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">stretch marks</a>, are streaks of reddened, thin skin that can occur as a result of rapid <a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/weight_gain/symptoms.htm" rel="sym" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">weight gain</a> or abdominal enlargement during <a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/pregnancy_planning_preparing_for_pregnancy/article.htm" rel="dt" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">pregnancy</a>. They can also occur in the setting of certain chronic disorders of the connective tissue. An excess of cortisol (<a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/cushings_syndrome/article.htm" rel="dt" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">Cushing's syndrome</a>) can also cause striae.
</p>.<p class="credits">REFERENCE:<br><br>Kasper, D.L., et al., eds. <i>Harrison's Principles of Internal Medicine, 19th Ed</i>. United States: McGraw-Hill Education, 2015.</p>